:"As further optimization, you can count, in typical runs, the actual number of times every case is chosen, and sort the cases from the most frequent to the less frequent."

I'd like to see benchmark figures for this (or for any other claim in this book, for that matter). The whole idea of a <code>switch</code> is that it can be compiled into a "computed goto" that uses the switch expression to determine how far to jump. The fastest switches are those for which all the cases are contiguous integers, i.e. without gaps as in:

<source lang="cpp">
switch (i) {
  case 0:
    // whatever
  case 1:
    // whatever
    // note: case 2 missing
  case 3:
    // whatever
}
</source>

... because in this case, the compiler needs to generate a check that <code>i != 2</code>. [[User:Qwertyus|Qwertyus]] ([[User talk:Qwertyus|discuss]] • [[Special:Contributions/Qwertyus|contribs]]) 14:19, 3 June 2014 (UTC)

