{{Refimprove|date=April 2014}} {{POV|date=April 2014}} [[File:Aalaapan - A Book Written By Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas.png|thumb|right|Cover of Aalaapan Book|300px]] '''''[[User:Aalaapan|Aalaapan]]''''' is a collection of poems by the [[Indian people|Indian]] poet [[User:Aalaapan/The Life of Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas|Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas]]<ref>Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas is an Indian Playback Singer. He has fame in the Geet Shudha and also in Bongiyo Sur Sangeet Kendra as Singer, Musician, Lyricist, Music Composer , Script and Screenplay writer , Poem and Story Writer. He got the title of Best Male Playback Singer from Bongiyo Sur Sangeet Kendra in the year 2012</ref>. The original [[Bengali people|Bengali]] collection of poems was published on April 14, 2014. ==A Note By "Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas"== [[File:Rahul Jaykar Ehsaas.jpg|thumb|right|RJ Ehsaas, Indian Poet]] " A poet is a person who writes poetry. A poet's work can be literal, meaning that his work is derived from a specific event, or metaphorical, meaning that his work can take on many meanings and forms. Poets have existed since antiquity, in nearly all languages, and have produced works that vary greatly in different cultures and time periods. Throughout each civilization and language, poets have used various styles that have changed through the course of literary history, resulting in a history of poets as diverse as the literature they have produced. The English word "poet" is derived from the French poète, itself descended from the Latin first-declension masculine noun poeta, meaning "poet". The word "poetry" derives from the Latin feminine noun poetria, meaning not "poetry" but "poetess". "A poet makes himself a visionary through a long, boundless, and systematized disorganization of all the senses. All forms of love, of suffering, of madness; he searches himself, he exhausts within himself all poisons, and preserves their quintessences. Unspeakable torment, where he will need the greatest faith, a superhuman strength, where he becomes all men: the great invalid, the great criminal, the great accursed—and the Supreme Scientist! For he attains the unknown! Because he has cultivated his soul, already rich, more than anyone! He attains the unknown, and, if demented, he finally loses the understanding of his visions, he will at least have seen them! So what if he is destroyed in his ecstatic flight through things unheard of, unnameable: other horrible workers will come; they will begin at the horizons where the first one has fallen!"
